	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The CAP towards 2020: Draft communication published by Commission</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A draft Commission communication on the future of the CAP towards 2020 has been posted. It maintains that there is a consensus on the need for ‘a strong common policy structured around its two pillars’ (direct aid payment and traditional market support instruments and the rural development pillar). It is considered that this policy should ‘preserve ... food production potential throughout the EU, so as to guarantee long-term food security for European citizens’, in the context of a projected 70% increase in global food demand by 2050. </p><p>The EC believes that pillar 1 ‘should contain the support paid to all farmers on a yearly basis’, while pillar 2 will give greater flexibility to EU member states to respond to specific concerns and problems. The EC argues that the introduction of direct aid payments has generated ‘market-orientated reforms’, which have enhanced ‘the competitiveness of the agricultural sector by encouraging farmers to adapt to market conditions’. Nevertheless a number of principles are advanced to guide the definition and rebalancing of the direct aid payment scheme:</p>
<ul>

<li>basic income support should be provided but with an upper ceiling;</li>

<li>payments should be linked to ‘greener’ measures, but with cross-compliance rules simplified;</li>

<li>additional support should be provided to areas with ‘specific natural constraints’;</li>

<li>voluntary coupled support should be allowed within clearly defined limits;</li>

<li>support should be targeted on more clearly defined ‘active farmers’.</li>

</ul>
<p>The basic architecture of market management tools is to be maintained. However, given the role of direct aid payments, traditional market management tools are increasingly being viewed by the EC as providing ‘merely a safety net’, for use in cases of ‘significant price declines’. Changes under consideration include: an extension of the period of intervention buying; a wider use of disturbance clause measures and private storage (e.g. extension to other products); improved controls of the use of such tools.</p><p>It notes that while the abolition of production quotas in the dairy sector has been agreed, in the sugar sector ‘several options for the future, including a non-disruptive end of the quotas at a date to be defined, need to be examined.’</p><p>Improving the function of the food supply chain, through addressing ‘the current imbalance of bargaining powers along the chain, the contractual relations, the need for restructuring and consolidation of the farm sector’, promoting greater transparency and addressing the functioning of agricultural commodity derivatives markets are all seen as potential areas for action.</p><p>The basic structure of the rural development pillar is endorsed, but with a greater focus on getting to grips with environmental and climate change issues and supporting innovation considered essential. A particular additional area being explored however is the establishment of a ‘risk management toolkit ... to deal more effectively within income uncertainties and market volatility.’ This, it is thought, could include optional measures ‘ranging from a new WTO green-box compatible income stabilisation tool, to strengthened support to insurance instruments and mutual funds.’ </p><p>A further strengthening and simplification of agricultural product quality policy and promotional measures is seen as necessary to enhance the competitiveness of the EU food and agricultural sector.</p><p>Maintaining the ‘capacity to deliver food security in time of crisis’ is seen as ‘an important long term choice for Europe’. </p><p>Considerable emphasis is placed on ‘releasing the latent productivity potential’ in new member states. The view is expressed that ‘targeting support exclusively to active farmers and remunerating the collective services they provide to society would increase the effectiveness and efficiency of support and further legitimise the CAP.’</p><p>Key challenges that a reformed CAP needs to address include: addressing global food security concerns; ensuring sustainable management of natural resources; ensuring continued competitiveness in an increasingly globalised economy subject to growing price volatility; addressing climate change effects; ensuring territorial and social cohesion across rural areas of the EU; and ensuring a more equitable and balanced distribution of benefits across EU member states.</p><p>The main objectives of a future CAP area are seen as:</p>
<ul>

<li>supporting farm income and limiting farm income variability;</li>

<li>improving the competitiveness of agriculture and enhancing farmers’ share of value from within the food chain;</li>

<li>supporting farmers facing particularly difficult natural constraints;</li>

<li>ensuring sustainable production practices and securing the provision of environmental goods;</li>

<li>fostering greener growth through innovation and pursuing climate change mitigation actions;</li>

<li>supporting rural employment and maintaining the social fabric of rural areas;</li>

<li>promoting diversification of rural economies, while allowing for structural diversity in European farming systems.</li>

</ul>
<p>It is argued that these objectives will require the maintenance of public support to the agricultural sector and rural development.</p><p>Against this background three broad policy options are seen as available:</p>
<ul>

<li>An ‘enhanced status quo’ option, involving building on current policies with ‘limited improvements in specific areas’;</li>

<li>A ‘more balanced, targeted and sustainable support’ option, involving introducing a major policy overhaul to promote ‘more sustainable’ targeting of support measures on specific policy objectives;</li>

<li>The ‘abolished market and income support option’, involving a radical reform of the CAP. </li>

</ul>
<p>The <i>EurActiv</i> EU policy and news network describes the EC communication in its analysis as ‘very green’. </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>European Commission, ‘
<a href="http://www.euractiv.fr/sites/default/files/communication_29_09_10.pdf" target="_self">The CAP Towards 2020: meeting the food, natural resource and territorial...</a>’, 29 September 2010.</p><p>
<a href="http://www.euractiv.fr/sites/default/files/communication_29_09_10.pdf" target="_self">http://www.euractiv.fr/sites/default/files/communication_29_09_10.pdf</a> </p><p><i>EurActiv.com</i>, ‘Premières indications de la Commission sur la future PAC’, 8 October 2010 (in French)</p><p>
<a href="http://www.euractiv.fr/premieres-indications-commission-future-pac-article" target="_self">http://www.euractiv.fr/premieres-indications-commission-future-pac-article</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The EC communication contains few details on potential proposals for reform, and is largely focused on setting out the broad policy framework. Since option 3 would involve ‘a significant reduction in production levels, farm income and the number of farmers’, this option is clearly not favoured by the EC, given the manner in which it has set out the challenges faced and the favoured policy objectives. The future of the CAP is thus likely to lie in a mixture of options 1 and 2. What precisely this is likely to entail is however not elaborated on in the current communication. Thus we find that while it is argued that the direct aid payment scheme should be restructured to be better targeted and more equitable, the fundamental question of how this is to be achieved is left unanswered.</p><p>One of the main proposals referred to, however, relating to the possible phasing out of production quotas as a market management tool in the sugar sector, is one which potentially has profound consequences for ACP sugar exporters. Against this background, the full implications of such a move for the use of other EU market management tools (e.g. reference prices and consequently EU market prices and EU external trade policy in the sugar sector) and their possible consequences for the ACP now need to be fully assessed. Particular attention should be paid to how the dismantling of national production quotas in the sugar sector can best be organised in such a way as to reduce the impact of such a move on the market prices paid for ACP sugar.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
